	<div id="id18e2" class="post">
		<h2 class="title"><span class="image-wrapper"><img height="45" alt="“Organic” label increasingly fishy" width="399" class="title" src="../../../resources/net.databinder.components.RenderedLabel/206d2082"/><span class="title">“Organic” label increasingly fishy</span></span></h2>
		<div class="byline"><span>
			<span>By <span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>, <span>on November 28, 2006</span></span>
			<span id="id18e3" class="tags">
					{&nbsp;<span><a href="../../../city/tag/organic/#selected-tag"><span>organic</span></a><span id="id18e4">, </span></span><span><a href="../../../city/tag/food/#selected-tag"><span>food</span></a><span id="id18e5">, </span></span><span><a href="../../../city/tag/nyt/#selected-tag"><span>nyt</span></a><span id="id18e6">, </span></span><span><a href="../../../city/tag/shopping/#selected-tag"><span>shopping</span></a><span id="id18e7">, </span></span><span><a href="../../../city/tag/culture/#selected-tag"><span>culture</span></a></span>&nbsp;}
			</span>
		</span></div>
		<div><h3>Remember being obsessed with hating labels?</h3>


	<p>During our Keedysville Thanksgiving (already <a href="http://technically.us/eat/articles/2006/11/24/raw-milk-party">partially documented</a> at <em>Eat</em>) we enjoyed some healthy ’90s nostalgia with a serving of late night <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roseanne_%28TV_series%29">Roseanne</a>. In the episode we watched, Darlene rebels against the “jock” label, apparently assigned to her by her parents, by dropping out of basketball. (Are you feeling nostalgic yet?)</p>


	<p>This doesn’t make sense. No one has actually called Darlene a “jock.” If anything, her problem is that she’s tired of the competition and her parents’ expectations, and is sinking into a typical post-pubescent malaise. Leave it to the 1990s to cast teenage angst as a rebellion against labels.</p>


	<p style="float:right"><img src="/pictures/bass-sm.jpg" alt="" /></p>


	<p>Unfortunately, label-haters of yore are worshiping today’s uber-label, <em>organic</em>. Like all labels, it’s useless. There’s no way to validate it. No one even knows what it means. The name itself is an affront to science, which had a precise definition for “organic” long before modern consumer-hippies turned it into slang for “good.”</p>


	<p>I’ve been chasing the organic fox <a href="/doc/articles/tag/organic">for a while</a> on this weblog, optimistically predicting it will die from overexposure or over-inclusion within the next few years. Looks like we’re on the verge of a big step towards the latter.</p>


	<h4>From <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/28/business/28fish.html">When Is a Fish Really Organic?</a>:</h4>


	<blockquote>
		<p>That is a question troubling the Agriculture Department, which decides such things. The answer could determine whether Americans will be able to add fish to the growing list of organic foods they are buying, and whether fish farmers will be able to tap into that trend and the profits that go with it.</p>
	</blockquote>


	<p>This set-up correctly points to the impetus behind the absurd <em>organic fish</em> question: capitalizing on the trend. It’s not as if anyone is sitting around wondering how well the fish on their plate ate, or was treated. People who care about that crap went vegan five years ago, at least. No, the standard bearers of this important cause are people like Rodger May.</p>


	<blockquote>
		<p> May, a Seattle businessman who sells wild and farm-raised salmon, is preparing for the day when he can sell his fish as organic. For now he refers to some of his farm-raised salmon — which live in ocean pens, as opposed to man-made ponds — as “natural,” a designation that does not carry the same marketing punch as would “organic.”</p>
	</blockquote>


	<p>Organic activism is long dead, replaced by a cold-blooded and highly profitable trade in synthetic health, environmentalism,  animal rights, and antipathy to science. Pay more for product O, and feel good. (I’d rather spend that money on alcohol.)</p>


	<p>If you really are concerned about the safety of eating fish, you could always consult someone who studies the topic. You know, through observation, experimentation, bubbling beakers…</p>


	<blockquote>
		<p>Trying to define what makes a fish organic “is a strange concept,” said George H. Leonard, science manager for the Seafood Watch Program at the Monterey Bay Aquarium, which offers a consumer guide to picking seafood. “I think the more you look at it, particularly for particular kinds of fish, it gets even stranger.”</p>
	</blockquote>


	<p><em>Organic fish</em>, a dumb idea according to everyone but the people looking to sell them. Not that it matters. We are a culture of consumers, and labelers, at heart.</p>


	<h4>And if there is any label Darlene would have fretted over, it’s “dyke.”</h4></div>
